qa_results.bill_summary: This bill requires paint manufacturers to establish and fund a program for the collection, transportation, and recycling of leftover architectural paint. Starting in 2026, a stewardship assessment fee will be added to the purchase price of paint sold in Maryland to cover the costs of this program. The Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) must review and approve program plans and annual reports, and paint producers must participate in the program to sell their products in the state.
qa_results.stakeholders: Paint producers, retailers, distributors, consumers of architectural paint, local governments, and the Maryland Department of the Environment.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: State special fund revenues and expenditures are estimated to increase by $70,200 in FY 2026 and $64,300 in FY 2027 to cover MDE's program oversight costs, which are fully offset by plan and report review fees paid by producers. Local governments may experience reduced household hazardous waste management costs. Consumers and government agencies will see a minimal increase in paint purchase costs due to the mandated stewardship assessment.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The Department of the Environment is the primary implementing agency for the bill. It oversees the Office of Recycling, which is responsible for reviewing and approving Paint Stewardship Program plans, setting assessment fees, managing the State Recycling Trust Fund, and enforcing compliance through penalties.

The bill explicitly requires the Office of Recycling to coordinate with the Maryland Environmental Service to study and report on recycling centers, public education needs, and the economics of waste disposal and recycling every two years.

As the agency responsible for the maintenance and construction of state-owned facilities, DGS is a significant consumer of architectural paint and will be impacted by the new paint stewardship assessments added to the purchase price of paint.
The Comptroller is the state's chief financial officer and is explicitly tasked by the bill to account for the State Recycling Trust Fund, which will receive program fees and penalties.
The State Treasurer is the custodian of the state's funds and is responsible for holding and investing the money within the State Recycling Trust Fund as established or amended by the bill.

The Governor's Office oversees executive departments like MDE and will receive several reports mandated by the bill, including the biennial recycling study and the specific cost-benefit review of the Paint Stewardship Program due in 2028.

DBM oversees state personnel and budgeting. The fiscal note indicates the need for a new contractual environmental compliance specialist at MDE to manage the additional workload created by the bill, requiring DBM's administrative oversight.

The OAG acts as the legal advisor to MDE and will be responsible for representing the state in enforcement actions and the collection of civil or administrative penalties for violations of the Paint Stewardship Program.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill authorizes Baltimore City and Maryland counties to establish a subclass of real property for vacant lots or improved properties cited as vacant and unfit for habitation. It further empowers these local governments to set a special property tax rate for this subclass and requires jurisdictions that do so to submit an annual report to the Department of Housing and Community Development and the General Assembly regarding the rate, revenue, and conversion plans for such properties.
qa_results.responsible_party: Mayor and City Council of Baltimore City, governing bodies of Maryland counties, and the Maryland Department of Housing and Community Development
qa_results.stakeholders: Owners of vacant and abandoned property, small businesses owning such properties, Baltimore City, and Maryland county governments
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: There is no impact on State finances. Local property tax revenues for Baltimore City and counties may increase or otherwise be affected depending on the specific tax rates set for the vacant property subclass. Small businesses owning these properties may experience a meaningful fiscal impact. Administrative reporting requirements for local governments are expected to be handled with existing resources.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The bill explicitly requires the Mayor and City Council of Baltimore City or the governing body of a county to report to this department annually by December 1. Specifically, jurisdictions must report the special rate set, the number of properties affected, revenue changes, and plans for adaptive reuse of these vacant properties. This aligns with the department's mission of neighborhood revitalization and managing programs to rehabilitate blighted areas.

As the principal executive agency, the Governor's Office is responsible for signing or vetoing legislation such as this bill. Furthermore, the bill addresses a significant statewide policy issue—vacant and abandoned property—which aligns with the office's initiative to improve economic opportunity and oversee the operations of state departments like DHCD.

The bill concerns land use and the classification of vacant real property for taxation. It specifically mentions 'adaptive reuse,' a key concept in historical preservation and urban planning managed by the Maryland Historical Trust and other planning services within this department. The department's mission is to ensure the vitality of communities and implement smart growth strategies.

The fiscal note identifies a potentially meaningful effect on small businesses that own vacant or abandoned property. The Department of Commerce is the state's primary agency for supporting small businesses and stimulating economic growth, including the revitalization of commercial properties and distressed areas.

The OAG serves as the primary legal advisor to the General Assembly and state agencies. They would be responsible for providing legal counsel regarding the implementation and interpretation of this new property tax subclass and the authority granted to local governments.

As the state's fiscal watchdog and chief financial officer, the Comptroller monitors state and local revenue structures. While this bill impacts local property taxes, the Comptroller's role in economic forecasting and financial reporting makes the fiscal implications of new property tax classes relevant to their oversight of the state's long-term fiscal health.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill prohibits Maryland institutions of higher education that receive State funds from considering an applicant's familial relationship to an alumnus (legacy preference) or to a financial donor (donor preference) as a criterion for admission. Institutions are still permitted to collect information about familial relationships to alumni for data collection purposes.
qa_results.responsible_party: Institutions of higher education in Maryland that receive State funds, including public, private nonprofit, and for-profit institutions.
qa_results.stakeholders: Applicants for admission to Maryland institutions of higher education, alumni, donors, and the administrative departments of public and private colleges and universities.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill is expected to have no material fiscal impact on State public four-year institutions or Baltimore City Community College, as any necessary changes to the admissions process can be managed with existing resources. Local community colleges are unaffected as they do not use legacy or donor preferences. While some private nonprofit institutions may see an impact on tuition revenue or alumni giving, the overall fiscal impact is assumed to be minimal and cannot be reliably estimated.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: MHEC is the state's primary regulatory and coordinating board for higher education, responsible for establishing statewide policies and overseeing both public and private institutions affected by the admissions standards prohibition.

MHEC is the state's primary regulatory and coordinating board for higher education, responsible for establishing statewide policies and overseeing both public and private institutions affected by the admissions standards prohibition.
USM is the primary public higher education agency overseeing 12 universities that are directly subject to the bill's prohibition on legacy and donor preferences in admissions.
As an independent public state university and state agency, Morgan State is directly prohibited by this bill from considering legacy or donor preferences in its admissions process.
As Maryland's public honors college and an independent state agency, Saint Mary's College is directly required to comply with the bill's restrictions on admissions criteria.
The OAG serves as the legal advisor for state institutions of higher education and will provide legal counsel on the implementation and enforcement of the new admissions standards.
The Governor's Office enforces state laws, signs legislation, and oversees the operations of all state departments and institutions, including the public universities implementing these changes.
The bill applies to any institution of higher education in the state that receives State funds; DBM is the central fiscal authority managing these allocations.

The MLDS Center maintains linked student and higher education data; the bill's provision allowing for the collection of familial relationship data for reporting purposes impacts the type of student records the agency manages.
OLA conducts fiscal and performance audits of executive branch agencies and universities; it would be responsible for auditing compliance with state-mandated admissions standards.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill codifies the common law crime of indecent exposure and establishes a new, more severe misdemeanor offense for committing indecent exposure with prurient intent in the presence of a minor. The new offense applies if the minor is at least two years old and more than four years younger than the offender. It increases the maximum penalty for this specific situation to five years of imprisonment and/or a $10,000 fine.
qa_results.responsible_party: Maryland Judiciary and the Department of Public Safety and Correctional Services
qa_results.stakeholders: Individuals charged with or convicted of indecent exposure, minors, the Maryland court system, and State and local correctional facilities.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill results in a minimal increase in State and local revenues and expenditures. State general fund revenues increase due to fines collected in District Court, while State expenditures increase minimally due to incarceration costs for longer sentences and potential payments to counties for inmate reimbursement. Local revenues and expenditures also increase minimally through circuit court fines and the costs of housing inmates in local detention facilities.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The bill codifies a common law crime and establishes a new criminal offense, directly impacting judicial proceedings. The fiscal note explicitly mentions the Judiciary's role in processing violations and provides data on charges and convictions in the District and circuit courts.

agency_relevance.agency_name: Department of Public Safety and Correctional Services
agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: DPSCS is responsible for the management of the state's correctional system, parole, and probation. The fiscal note details the impact on incarceration costs and identifies that the Division of Correction and Division of Parole and Probation will manage individuals sentenced under the bill's provisions.

agency_relevance.agency_name: Maryland Office of the Public Defender
agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The Office of the Public Defender is responsible for providing legal representation to indigent residents. The fiscal note specifically notes that the agency expects an increase in caseloads requiring additional staffing due to the new criminal offense defined by the bill.
As the principal executive agency, the Governor's Office is responsible for signing or vetoing legislation. Governor Wes Moore signed this specific bill (Chapter 858) into law.

agency_relevance.agency_name: Governor's Office of Crime Prevention and Policy
agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: This agency serves as the state's central hub for public safety policy. This bill alters criminal law and penalties, which falls under their purview for advising the Governor on criminal justice strategies.

The Maryland State Police are responsible for enforcing criminal laws statewide. This bill establishes a new criminal misdemeanor that their officers would be responsible for investigating and charging.
The OAG handles criminal appeals in state and federal courts. Any appeals resulting from convictions under this new subsection of the Criminal Law Article would be managed by this agency.

The Comptroller is the state's tax collector and fiscal watchdog. The bill's penalty provisions include fines of up to $10,000, which contribute to the state's general fund revenues managed by the Comptroller.

The Governor's Office for Children leads policy efforts to improve the well-being of children. This bill is specifically designed to protect minors from indecent exposure by creating a enhanced penalty for offenses committed in their presence.

qa_results.bill_summary: The Housing Innovation Pilot Program Act of 2024 establishes the Housing Innovation Pilot Program and the Housing Innovation Fund within the Department of Housing and Community Development. The program provides low-interest or no-interest loans to local housing authorities and county governments to develop mixed-income, cross-subsidized housing projects that are publicly owned or controlled and serve households earning between 50% and 60% of the area median income.
qa_results.responsible_party: Department of Housing and Community Development
qa_results.stakeholders: Local housing authorities, county governments, private housing developers, and low-to-moderate income Maryland residents qualifying for affordable housing.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill increases state special fund revenues and expenditures by $10 million in FY 2025 and $5 million annually from FY 2026 through 2029, often via the reallocation of existing rental housing program funds. General fund expenditures increase by $170,535 in FY 2025 for department administrative staffing and costs, with subsequent annual increases for inflation. Local governments and housing authorities will see increased revenues and expenditures as they receive and expend loan funds for housing projects.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: As the primary implementing agency, DHCD is responsible for establishing and administering the Housing Innovation Pilot Program and the associated Housing Innovation Fund, including soliciting applications and selecting projects for funding.

The Governor is authorized to include annual appropriations of $5,000,000 in the state budget for the program and exercises executive oversight over the agency's implementation of this new housing policy initiative.
The bill explicitly mandates that the State Treasurer hold the Housing Innovation Fund separately and invest the money of the fund in the same manner as other state money.
The bill explicitly requires the Comptroller to account for the newly established Housing Innovation Fund.

DBM oversees the state's annual budget process and the allocation of the $5 million annual appropriation authorized by the bill, and manages the personnel needs (1.5 positions) identified in the fiscal note.
The bill prioritizes housing projects that include a commitment to prevailing wage requirements, which falls under the regulatory and enforcement domain of the Department of Labor.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill authorizes a condominium regime to be established on a leasehold estate owned by an affordable housing land trust.
qa_results.responsible_party: Secretary of State and State Department of Assessments and Taxation
qa_results.stakeholders: Affordable housing land trusts, low-income families, and moderate-income families
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill is not anticipated to materially affect State or local government finances or operations. Small business impact is expected to be minimal.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The bill focuses on affordable housing land trusts, which are central to the Department's mission to expand access to affordable housing and support neighborhood revitalization. DHCD is also identified in the fiscal note as a key agency for implementation.

The Secretary of State is responsible for the registration of residential condominiums in Maryland and oversees the registration of charitable organizations, which are the entities specifically authorized to manage affordable housing land trusts.

Condominium regimes are established by recording declarations and plats in the county land records. The Administrative Office of the Courts maintains the administrative and technological infrastructure, such as public records portals, used for these legal filings.

The agency coordinates land use and sustainable growth strategies; authorizing land trusts to establish condominium regimes impacts urban design, infrastructure management, and community planning policies overseen by the department.

The OAG serves as the primary legal advisor for the executive branch and its agencies. It provides essential legal counsel regarding changes to real property law, condominium regulations, and the statutory powers of land trusts.

As the principal executive agency, the Governor's Office signed this bill into law and oversees the Department of Housing and Community Development and other agencies implementing statewide affordable housing initiatives.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill requires the State Department of Assessments and Taxation to maintain a website for voluntary donations to the Homeowner Protection Program, which provides assistance to low-income, elderly, and disabled homeowners to prevent tax sale foreclosure. Additionally, local tax collectors must include a separate informational insert with each property tax bill that describes the program and encourages taxpayers to make a donation through the state website.
qa_results.responsible_party: State Department of Assessments and Taxation
qa_results.stakeholders: Low-income, elderly, and disabled homeowners; Maryland property owners; local government tax collectors
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: State special fund revenues will increase starting in FY 2025 from voluntary donations to the Homeowner Protection Fund, though the total amount cannot be reliably estimated. Local government expenditures will increase to cover the costs of including the required inserts in property tax bills, with estimated costs ranging from $3,200 to $70,000 annually per jurisdiction.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The bill requires the Governor to include a specific annual appropriation of $750,000 in the budget for the Homeowner Protection Fund through fiscal 2025, which aligns with the office's responsibility for drafting the state's annual budget.

As the state's chief financial officer and tax collector, the Comptroller oversees fiscal policies and revenue collection. While property taxes are local, the bill involves state-level tax policy and the management of a state special fund.
The Treasurer is the custodian of state funds, including the management and investment of public funds like the Homeowner Protection Fund mentioned in the bill.

The OAG serves as the legal advisor for state agencies, including the State Department of Assessments and Taxation (SDAT), which is tasked with maintaining the donation website and the Homeowner Protection Program.

The Homeowner Protection Program explicitly targets elderly homeowners to prevent loss of homes through tax sale foreclosure, aligning with the Department of Aging's mission to advocate for and provide services to older adults.
DBM oversees the state budget and the allocation of taxpayer resources; the bill mandates specific budget appropriations and the management of a special fund.

The bill's funding mechanism supports a program that protects disabled homeowners from tax sale foreclosure, which falls under the Department of Disabilities' mandate to ensure independence and community-based living for individuals with disabilities.
Preventing tax sale foreclosure is a critical component of housing stability and homelessness prevention, which are core missions of the Department of Housing and Community Development.

Tax sale foreclosures are judicial proceedings. The Administrative Office of the Courts manages the infrastructure of the judiciary and provided information for the fiscal note regarding the bill's impact.
The Maryland Tax Court adjudicates tax-related grievances, including those related to property assessments which underpin the tax sales addressed by the Homeowner Protection Program.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill requires charter counties and certain code counties in Maryland to include an assessment of fair housing in the housing element of their comprehensive plans. The assessment must demonstrate that the county is affirmatively furthering fair housing by taking actions to overcome patterns of segregation and fostering inclusive communities free from housing barriers.
qa_results.responsible_party: The Maryland Department of Planning, the Department of Housing and Community Development, and charter and code county governments.
qa_results.stakeholders: Residents of Maryland charter and code counties, particularly those seeking low-income and workforce housing, and local planning commissions.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill's requirements can be implemented by the State with existing resources, and revenues are not affected. The bill is not expected to have a direct, material impact on local government finances, as many jurisdictions already prepare similar assessments for federal funding requirements.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: As the agency that requested this departmental bill, MDP is primarily responsible for providing technical assistance to charter counties to develop the housing element of their comprehensive plans and ensuring compliance with land use requirements.
DHCD is explicitly tasked with providing technical assistance to counties in consultation with MDP. The bill also relies on housing definitions and fair housing standards managed by this agency.

MCCR is responsible for enforcing anti-discrimination laws in housing. The bill's mandate for counties to assess and affirmatively further fair housing directly aligns with the commission's mission to overcome patterns of segregation.
The OAG serves as the legal advisor to the state agencies (MDP and DHCD) implementing this law and provides guidance on the rule of law regarding fair housing and civil rights.

The department coordinates policy for accessible housing. Affirmatively furthering fair housing requires assessing and removing barriers for individuals with disabilities, a core focus of this agency.

The department advocates for equitable access to essential resources for older adults. Assessment of fair housing in comprehensive plans must account for the specific housing needs and potential barriers faced by Maryland's aging population.

This multi-agency initiative coordinates state land-use and sustainable growth efforts. Incorporating fair housing assessments into county comprehensive plans is a key component of sustainable and equitable community development.

The Governor's Office oversees all state departments and signs legislation. This bill supports statewide initiatives spearheaded by the office to improve economic opportunity and community well-being through equitable housing policy.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill officially changes the common name of the northern snakehead to 'Chesapeake Channa' in Maryland. It renames the commercial fishing license accordingly and mandates that the Department of Natural Resources adopt regulations and update all published materials to reflect this name change by January 1, 2025.
qa_results.stakeholders: Commercial fishers, small businesses in the seafood industry, and the Maryland Department of Natural Resources.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: The bill can be implemented using existing State resources and has no local fiscal impact. It may have a potential meaningful impact on small businesses in the commercial fishing and seafood industry if the rebranding leads to increased marketing and harvesting of the species.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: The Department of Natural Resources is the primary agency responsible for implementing this bill. It is specifically mandated to adopt regulations establishing the 'Chesapeake Channa' name, rename the commercial fishing license, and ensure the new name is used on all departmental publications.

The Department of Agriculture is involved in seafood marketing through initiatives like 'Maryland's Best.' Renaming the invasive northern snakehead to the more marketable 'Chesapeake Channa' directly impacts their efforts to promote local seafood and was identified as a stakeholder in the fiscal note.

The MFCA operates the Maryland Market Center (Seafood Market) in Jessup. Renaming a commercially harvested species affects the distribution, inventory, and labeling of products within the state's primary wholesale seafood distribution hub.

The Department of Commerce supports small businesses and marketing for local industries. The fiscal note suggests the bill may have a meaningful economic impact on small businesses in the commercial fishing and seafood sectors by potentially increasing demand.

This multi-agency initiative focuses on the health of the Chesapeake Bay. Renaming an invasive species to include 'Chesapeake' in its name aligns with the initiative's efforts to coordinate branding and environmental stewardship of the Bay's ecosystem.

The OAG serves as the legal advisor for state agencies and will be responsible for providing legal counsel and reviewing the new regulations mandated by the bill for the Department of Natural Resources.

The Governor's Office oversees all executive agencies and departments, including the implementation of new legislation and the coordination of the executive branch's response to invasive species and economic development.

qa_results.bill_summary: This bill requires the Maryland State Highway Administration (SHA) to update its pollinator habitat plan to include policies that encourage the use of native plants, establish habitat areas along state highways, and educate the public about these efforts. SHA is also mandated to track and apply for federal funding related to pollinator habitats and invasive species control, and must publish annual updates including the locations and sizes of maintained habitat areas.
qa_results.stakeholders: Pollinators, the general public (drivers, bicyclists, and pedestrians), community associations, and the Maryland Department of Transportation.
qa_results.fiscal_impact_summary: State Transportation Trust Fund expenditures are expected to increase minimally, likely by less than $50,000 annually, including an estimated $35,000 in fiscal 2025 for signage and public outreach events. There is a potential increase in federal fund revenues if SHA successfully applies for and receives federal grants for pollinator habitats.

agency_relevance.relevance_explanation: SHA is the primary agency responsible for implementing the bill, including updating its pollinator habitat plan, developing policies for native plants, maintaining habitat areas along highways, and tracking/applying for federal funding for these purposes.

As the parent agency of SHA, MDOT is impacted by the bill's requirements and the associated fiscal impact on the Transportation Trust Fund. The bill governs operations along the state highway network managed by its business unit.
The bill amends the Agriculture Article and explicitly requires SHA to consult with the Department of Agriculture when establishing and maintaining its pollinator habitat plan.
DNR is one of the three agencies, along with SHA and MES, that is statutory required to establish and maintain a pollinator habitat plan and make it available to the public.

MES is one of the three agencies required by statute to establish a pollinator habitat plan and share it on its website. It also provides technical and operational services for environmental projects that overlap with the bill's conservation goals.
The Secretary of Health is responsible for determining if the use of toxic pesticides, otherwise prohibited by a pollinator habitat plan, is necessary to respond to specific public health threats.

The bill requires SHA to track and evaluate federal programs that provide funding for pollinator habitats and native plants, which falls within the Grants Office's mission to maximize federal funding for state agencies.

This multi-agency initiative coordinates stewardship of the state's natural resources and land-use policies among the departments of Agriculture, Natural Resources, and Transportation, all of which are involved in the pollinator plan mandate.
